  "text": "Traditionally IBS has no serious consequences. However, because of the relation with anxiety and depression, a study that compared one hundred followup, tertiary care IBS (tIBS) patients, with 100 secondary IBS (sIBS), 100 primary IBS (pIBS) care patients, and 100 patients with active inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) evidenced that 38% of tIBS patients had contemplated suicide because of their symptoms compared with 16% and 4% in the sIBS and pIBS groups (tIBS vs. sIBS vs. pIBS, P= .002, P< .001). Five tIBS and 1 IBD patient had attempted suicide for reasons related with gastrointestinal symptoms. Hopelessness because of symptom severity, interference with professional life, and inefficient treatment were emphasized as main issues for IBS patients [CITATION_1] .",
